28. 90. nihil recusans: nihil is wanting in the Mss.; and Peter prefers to supply dicere, = ‘declining to speak ’ς cf. de Off. 111. 27. 100, sententiam ne diceret recusavit, and Holden's note.

26. 100. habita est, optima est: Β. and K.; most editions have esset.

28. 107. occisus est: B. and Κ. 3 al. esset (cs. 100).

29.110. etiamsi,etc..· Β. and Κ. bracket as far as industria3 but quamquam cannot well point to anything but probabiles industria. Jahn brackets only to essent3 then tamen looks back to laudandi. Stangl reads et, vel si.

29.112. lectu: for Mss. acta.

quidem, sed neque tam nostris: Mahly (Rh. Mus, 20. 639) changes to quidem neque tamen nostris.

81. 117. tribunatu: a reading generally adopted sor the MsS. trium· viratu3 ⁴ coni. Sch. ,· certe probabilius est tribunos iudicio intercessisse, quam cum Bernhardyo triumviros capitales significari putare',· Ell. ,

sicut etiam: a somewhat doubtful emendation os the Mss. sunt etiam.

is . . disputando: bracketedby Jahn. W. Friedrich (Jahrb. 107) suggests that the name of another Stoic (not quite horridus) may have dropped out, to whom the is refers.

81. 120. id . . . Academia: bracketed or omitted by most editors as a gloss.

31. 121. sic aiunt: the Mss. reading is sic ut aiunt philosophi, etc.; ‘ sic ut corruptum est ex sic aiunt’ ,· Ell.

84. 129. luculentus accusator: most of the Mss. (not all, Marg. p. 14) have luculentus patronus. For the first word some editions substitute lutulentus, others truculentus ; while most omit patronus. If lucu· lentus is left to stand alone, it may = bright, lively3 cf. the good ternis below, Peter justifies luculentus patronus, saying, Oratio igitur lucu- lenta est, in qua lux veritatis, perspicuitatis inest ,⁶ auctor luculentus, in cuius testimonio eadem illa lux inest: . . . id autem in patrono paullo audacius transferri, facile intellegitur. Perhaps patronus should be retained.

34. 130. atque etiam: W. Friedrich (Jahrb. 121) changes etiam to et acri. B. and K. read acuto etiarm Pid., atque iam.

85. 132. nisi quid fieri potest: Mahly (Rh. Mus. 20. 639) supports the reading nisi quod fieri potest ; cf. Pid. note.

87. 140. proprie: several editors adopt an emendation of Lambinus, propria.

88.142, conquestionibus· the Mss. have questionibus (not else— where found).

88. 143. ita. bracketed by B. & Κ. If it is retained, we may with Pid. supply ut dicerent.

42. 153. quorum similia nulla sunt. H. A. Koch (Rh. Mus. 16. 485) conjectures quorum volumina multa sunt.
